Worsted on the theory of the question, Mendacium then falls back on the practical difficulties in the way of dis- endowment, and the consideration of these occupies Chapters 24—33. Finally in 34-36 Veritas briefly shows the part which each order of the Church has to play, traces the history of endowment, and points out the advantages to be gained by its abolition. In the Epi- logus, which is scholastic in form, new arguments are added, with a recapitulation of some of the most im- portant points previously made.

As an introduction to his arguments, Veritas briefly describes the division of the Church Militant into the three orders of Clerus, Domini Temporales, and VulgareS, and explains their several functions and relations.
